MGA Millennium (MGA2064W) with Ti3026 RAMDAC driver v1.0

Features:

* Basic support for the Matrox Millennium video adapter
* basic bitblt support
* uses linear frame buffer whenever possible
* it should be possible to reach resolutions upto 1920x1024
* it should be possible to use pixel depths of 8, 16, and 32 bits
  per pixel (256 pseudo colour, "high colour", "true colour"). 
  Sorry, 24 bpp is not supported at this time (although we will
  look into it).

Future Features (in order from highest to lowest priority)

=1	more hardware acceleration (hw cursor, more primitive operations, etc)
=1	3d acceleration (once we work out how that's done)
2	more chipsets and RAMDACs

Technical Note:

This driver is the work of Radoslaw Kapitan for the most part, when he did
not have the required Matrox documentation. The driver has been cleaned up
and corrected, and should work on most Matrox Millennium boards.

!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!
This first release that was integrated in XFree86-3.1.2Gg contains
several hacks to get this to work. Especially, it won't work when the
MMIO registers aren't mapped correctly. Most of the updated PCI
detection and access code should at least be rethought.
!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!

Reference releases, which are quality tested and are known to work are in
the base XFree86 3.2 and later source tree. If you don't like your machine
crashing, we suggest you stick to those stable releases.

Radoslaw's board is a 4 MB, 220 MHz Matrox Millennium, and we know that one
works okay. :-)

Hardware Supported:

This driver only supports the MGA Storm (MGA2064W) chipset with the TI
(TVP) 3026 RAMDAC. Matrox have only so far made 175 and 220 MHz boards with
these two components, although 135 and 250 MHz RAMDAC parts exist.

The driver assumes a 2 MB, 175 MHz DAC card. We are trying to get the
automatic detection of WRAM and DAC Speed worked out. You can configure it
to use the 220 MHz DAC and more WRAM, but please only do so once you are
certain that you have the faster RAMDAC and/or more WRAM (see your card's
technical documentation).

We will eventually provide support for the other Matrox chipsets (once the
Millenium driver is at a far enough stage and more people with other cards
join the effort), including the Impression, Mystique, etc. The Mystique may
even work (depends on how much has changed, whether the RAMDAC is still the
3026... etc). If you are a non-Millennium Matrox owner, please do not try
this Xserver out unless you are certain that your board has the required
RAMDAC and chipset.

Configuration:

If you have a 220 MHz board, you must specify in the XF86Config file the
following line (near where Videoram or Clocks is commented out).

DACSpeed 	220

If you have more video ram than 2 MB, you MUST specify the amount in the
following fashion:

4 mb boards:

Videoram	4096

8 mb boards:

Videoram	8192

Other options:

"nolinear"				- disables linear frame buffer and BitBlt Engine
"noaccel", "no_bitblt"	- turns off BitBlt Engine

Virtual Widths:

The following multiples must be honored for virtual widths to work:

bpp		non-interleave	interleave
8		64				128
16		32				64
32		32				32

This table may be wrong - another table in the documentation has these
values the other way around, and the last row reads 32 16 32. Go figure!

2 MB boards have to use non-interleaved WRAM accesses for technical
reasons, but 4 and 8 MB WRAM configurations should be using interleaved
accesses for faster throughput. 4 MB boards can work in both interleaved
and non-interleaved modes. We will work out how to determine this in
future releases. 

If you don't understand this discussion, don't worry, we don't either (yet)
and once we get it sorted out, you cannot make a mistake.

For now, stick to nice virtual widths, like 640 800 1024 1152 1280 and so
on. If you can divide your proposed virtual width by 128, you'll be safe.

